The consumer protection framing is the right anchor — PRISM's functional 
value is making implicit expert heuristics explicit, auditable, and comparable 
across transactions in a market where asymmetric information is the primary 
mechanism of exploitation. A new collector being quoted $800 for a wulfenite 
specimen doesn't know what they don't know; PRISM makes the scoring criteria 
legible and the price deviation from comparable specimens visible.

The most important algorithmic challenge to design around early is species-specific 
scoring benchmarks. "Crystal quality" has fundamentally different parameter 
definitions for a wulfenite tabletop, an elbaite indicolite, and a rhodochrosite 
rhombohedron — a universal rubric applied naively produces scores that are 
meaningless as within-species comparisons. The architecture that avoids this 
becoming technical debt: universal feature parameters at the scoring engine 
(crystal symmetry expression, surface condition index, matrix relationship 
quality, chromophore saturation, termination completeness), with species-specific 
benchmark distributions derived from Mindat occurrence data that convert raw 
feature values into within-species percentile ranks. The Mindat REST API at 
api.mindat.org has the structured species and locality data, but a locally-cached 
species table is advisable for convention floor environments with unreliable 
connectivity.

For the legal compliance GIS layer, PADUS (Protected Areas Database of the 
United States, USGS National Geospatial Program) is the primary domestic dataset; 
WDPA (World Database on Protected Areas, UNEP-WCMC) handles international coverage. 
The legal complexity extends considerably beyond national park status: BLM casual 
use doctrine under FLPMA permits personal amounts but prohibits commercial 
collection without a permit; ARPA (16 U.S.C. §470aa) applies wherever cultural 
material older than 100 years is associated with the site; and country-specific 
export control regimes — Afghanistan's 2002 Cultural Property Export Law, Brazil's 
CFEM royalty framework, DRC mineral moratoria — affect international provenance 
evaluation. The date-of-first-collection field is well conceived and should 
cross-reference regulatory enactment dates, since a specimen collected from what 
is now a protected area in 1945 was collected legally.

The NHMLAC donation module maps directly onto IRS Form 8283 requirements: non-cash 
charitable contributions exceeding $5,000 require a qualified appraisal under 
Treasury Regulation §1.170A-13. The PRISM documentation sub-score could be 
structured to produce a report explicitly addressing those appraisal 
requirements — appraiser qualification, property description, fair market 
value methodology, and basis documentation. This use case extends 
well beyond NHMLAC; any museum receiving mineral donations needs a standardized 
pre-screening protocol, and that's a meaningful institutional licensing pathway.

For market data: raw scraped listing prices are informationally noisy since 
listed price doesn't equal realized price and condition is rarely standardized. 
The signal that protects buyers is price per PRISM-score-unit, segmented by 
species and locality tier, calibrated against realized sale prices from Heritage 
Auctions, Bonhams, and accessible dealer invoiced sales. This enables precise 
anomaly flagging at point-of-sale: "comparable specimens at this PRISM score 
range have realized X–X–X–Y; this listing is at 3.4× median." For the certificate 
system, the QR code should encode a verification URL pointing to a server-side record 
rather than the score locally — store a SHA-256 hash of the assessment image set 
at the time of scoring to prevent post-hoc specimen substitution.
