The most consequential design decision visible in that architecture 
is that the weights feeding into the PRISM score need to be context-specific, 
not universal. Museum grade should heavily weight provenance and scientific 
value (the documentation sub-score carries the institutional compliance 
function); Exhibition grade should weight aesthetics and crystal quality; 
Commercial grade should weight market price benchmarking most heavily. A single 
specimen gets a different contextualized score depending on the evaluation 
purpose, which is actually more analytically honest than a single number.